Spacetime split
In spacetime algebra, a spacetime split is a projection from four-dimensional space into (3+1)-dimensional space in a chosen reference frame by means of the following two operations:

a collapse of the chosen time axis, yielding a 3D space spanned by bivectors, equivalent to the standard 3D basis vectors in the algebra of physical space and
a projection of the 4D space onto the chosen time axis, yielding a 1D space of scalars, representing the scalar time.This is achieved by pre- or post-multiplication by a timelike basis vector 
  
    
      
        
          γ
          
            0
          
        
      
    
    {\displaystyle \gamma _{0}}
  , which serves to split a four vector into a scalar timelike and a bivector spacelike component, in the reference frame co-moving with 
  
    
      
        
          γ
          
